The paper focuses on lower bounds and algorithms for geometric problems, which suggests that it belongs to the computational geometry (cs.CG) sub-category. The use of the streaming model implies that it may also belong to the data structures (cs.DS) sub-category. The consideration of discrepancy suggests that it may belong to the discrete mathematics (cs.DM) sub-category. The use of randomized algorithms suggests that it may also belong to the computational complexity (cs.CC) sub-category. Finally, the use of approximation algorithms suggests that it may also belong to the information theory (cs.IT) sub-category.
